The record high of 8 million square miles was recorded in 1980, and the previous record low was recorded in June of 2007. The current record low as of August 2012 rests below 2 million square miles. A black line depicts the shrinkage of the Arctic sea ice, while the orange line depicts the 1979-200 average seasonal low. The map on the right outlines the shrinkage area on a globe from NASA satellite imagery.
